    <body>
        <div xml:id="NA397-kiḷavi">
            <p type="edition">itu piriviṭai āṟṟāḷāki (ET: āy) niṉṟa talaimakaḷai vaṟpuṟāniṉṟa
                (ET: vaṟpuṟutta) tōḻikku “āṟṟuval” eṉpatupaṭac colliyatu.</p>
            <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what was spoken in order say “I can bear it” to the confidante who was encouraging HER who stood [there], being unable to bear it in the time of separation.</p>
            </div>
      <div xml:id="NA397">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            tōḷu maḻiyu nāḷuñ ceṉṟeṉa</l>
<l>            nīḷiṭai yatta nōkki vāḷaṟṟuk</l>
<l>            kaṇṇuṅ kāṭci tauviṉa veṉṉīt</l>
<l>            taṟivu mayaṅkip piṟitā kiṉṟē</l>
<l>            nōyum pēru mālaiyum vantaṉ</l>
<l>            ṟiyāṅkā kuveṉkol yāṉē yīṅkō</l>
<l>            cāta lañcēṉ añcuval cāviṟ</l>
<l>            piṟappuppiṟi tākuva tāyiṉ</l>
<l>            maṟakkuveṉ kolleṉ kātala ṉeṉavē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>            The shoulders are perishing and, since all the days go by,</l>
<l rend="indent">            looking at the road, a long way, while light subsides<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vāḷ aṟṟu</term>: here we have one of these interestingly inserted absolutives that change subject, in between a row of classical absolutives.</note>,</l>
<l>        [my] eyes have lessened in sight,</l>
<l rend="indent4">            and, leaving me,</l>
<l>        knowledge has become something confusingly different.</l>
<l>        Pain too is becoming big and evening has come.</l>
<l>        What will become of me?</l>
<l rend="indent4">            As for that(?),</l>
<l>        I don’t fear dying.</l>
<l rend="indent4">            I fear, if I die,</l>
<l rend="indent">            if birth becomes another,</l>
<l>        will I forget that he [is] my lover?</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
